=== PRIORITY 1: VISION MODEL — Photo-based Food Logging ===

Implement Qwen3-VL-2B vision model support for photo-based food logging.

Steps:
1. Research how llama.cpp handles vision models (llava-style API)
   - Look at llama.cpp examples/llava/ for the C API usage
   - Check if our source-built xcframework (b7310) includes vision/clip headers
   - If not, rebuild xcframework with vision support enabled

2. Implement vision pipeline in LlamaCppBackend:
   - Load mmproj (multimodal projector) alongside the main model
   - Add method: processImage(UIImage) -> image embeddings
   - Add method: respondWithImage(prompt, image) -> text response
   - Keep existing text-only respond() working

3. Download and test Qwen3-VL-2B model:
   - Files already on GitHub releases: Qwen3-VL-2B-Instruct-Q4_K_M.gguf + mmproj
   - Update AIModelTier to include a vision tier
   - Test on simulator first

4. Add photo food logging UI:
   - Camera button in AI chat
   - Take photo or pick from gallery
   - Send to vision model: "What food is in this image? Estimate calories."
   - Parse response → open food log sheet pre-filled

5. Add nutrition label scanning via vision:
   - Photo of nutrition label → vision model extracts macros

=== PRIORITY 2: AI CHAT QUALITY ===

The AI chat must be world-class at three things:

1) FOOD LOGGING VIA CHAT
   - Multi-turn conversation: "I had rice" → "how much?" → "1 cup" → logged
   - Handle ambiguity: "I had coffee" → "black or with milk?" → smart follow-up
   - Show what the agent is doing: "Searching for rice..." → "Found: Rice (206cal)"
   - Handle corrections: "actually it was 3 not 2"

2) NATURAL CONVERSATION FLOW
   - Context should flow naturally between turns
   - AI should remember what was discussed in the session
   - When AI doesn't know, ask clarifying questions instead of guessing
   - Keep responses under 3 sentences unless user asks for detail

3) WORKOUT TEMPLATE CREATION VIA CHAT
   - "I want to do a push day" → show available templates or help create one
   - "Add bench press 3x10" → build a workout step by step
   - Let them start the workout from chat

=== PRIORITY 3: MODEL EVALUATION HARNESS ===

Build gold-standard test harness for evaluating LLM quality:
- 50+ synthetic queries with expected responses
- Measure precision (correct actions) and recall (handled vs fallback)
- Score response quality
- Easy to swap models and compare
- Run as part of test suite

=== PRIORITY 4: INFERENCE OPTIMIZATION ===

Speed without quality loss:
- Check if newer llama.cpp (b8000+) fixed the Metal bfloat/half shader bug
- Try building with GGML_METAL_USE_BF16=OFF to disable bfloat
- Profile where time is spent: tokenization vs prompt eval vs generation
- Try different quantizations: Q4_K_M vs Q5_K_M — benchmark quality vs speed
- Research: can we use Apple's Neural Engine via CoreML?

=== PRIORITY 5: MEDICAL REPORT EXTRACTION ===

When AI model is loaded, use it to improve:
- Lab report OCR: LLM fallback exists — test with real reports, improve accuracy
- Nutrition label parsing: use LLM to extract from photos when regex fails
- Food name normalization: "PBJ" → "peanut butter and jelly sandwich"

=== PRIORITY 6: BUG HUNTING ===

Before adding features, ensure stability:
- Look at recent commits — that's where bugs hide
- Write tests for every new feature
- Check edge cases: empty DB, no HealthKit, no internet, model not downloaded
- Test full flow: download model → load → chat → log food → verify in Food tab

